SIMPLE: flirt
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flirt
<hw>Flirt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Flirted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flirting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>fleard</ets>
trifle, folly, <ets>fleardian</ets> to trifle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To throw with a jerk or quick effort; to fling suddenly; <as>as,
they <ex>flirt</ex> water in each other's faces; he <ex>flirted</ex> a
glove, or a handkerchief.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To toss or throw about; to move playfully to and
fro; <as>as, to <ex>flirt</ex> a fan</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To jeer at; to treat with contempt; to mock.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am ashamed; I am scorned; I am <qex>flirted</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flirt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flirt
<hw>Flirt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To run and dart about;
to act with giddiness, or from a desire to attract notice; especially,
to play the coquette; to play at courtship; to coquet; <as>as, they
<ex>flirt</ex> with the young men</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter contemptuous language, with an air of
disdain; to jeer or gibe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Beau. &
Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flirt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flirt
<hw>Flirt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden jerk; a quick
throw or cast; a darting motion; hence, a jeer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Several little <qex>flirts</qex> and vibrations.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With many a <qex>flirt</qex> and flutter.</q> <rj><qau>E. A.
Poe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Cf. LG. <ets>flirtje</ets>, G.
<ets>flirtchen</ets>. See <er>Flirt</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<def>One who flirts; esp., a woman who acts with giddiness, or plays at
courtship; a coquette; a pert girl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Several young <qex>flirts</qex> about town had a design to cast us
out of the fashionable world.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flirt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Flirt
<hw>Flirt</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pert; wanton.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flirtation</ent>⟦br⟧
